{"PageNumber":2,"Angle":0,"RotatedAngle":0,"Height":2376,"Width":1836,"OriginHeight":0,"OriginWidth":0,"Elements":[{"Index":0,"Type":"title","Text":"#  2.6 Proxy Method","Level":0,"Polygon":{"LeftBottom":{"X":210,"Y":252},"LeftTop":{"X":210,"Y":214},"RightBottom":{"X":454,"Y":252},"RightTop":{"X":454,"Y":214}},"InsetImageName":"","Elements":null,"ImagePath":"","group_id":-1,"group_type":""},{"Index":1,"Type":"paragraph","Text":"Proxy Method is a structural design pattern, it provides a substitute for an object, which can act as an intermediary or control access to the real object.","Level":0,"Polygon":{"LeftBottom":{"X":202,"Y":345},"LeftTop":{"X":202,"Y":257},"RightBottom":{"X":1627,"Y":345},"RightTop":{"X":1627,"Y":257}},"InsetImageName":"","Elements":null,"ImagePath":"","group_id":-1,"group_type":""},{"Index":2,"Type":"title","Text":"##  2.7 Flyweight Method","Level":0,"Polygon":{"LeftBottom":{"X":210,"Y":428},"LeftTop":{"X":210,"Y":388},"RightBottom":{"X":509,"Y":428},"RightTop":{"X":509,"Y":388}},"InsetImageName":"","Elements":null,"ImagePath":"","group_id":-1,"group_type":""},{"Index":3,"Type":"paragraph","Text":"Flyweight Method is a structural design pattern, it is used when we need to create a lot of objects of a class. Since every object consumes memory space that can be crucial for low memory devices, flyweight design patterns can be applied to reduce the load on memory by sharing objects.","Level":0,"Polygon":{"LeftBottom":{"X":202,"Y":561},"LeftTop":{"X":202,"Y":431},"RightBottom":{"X":1627,"Y":561},"RightTop":{"X":1627,"Y":431}},"InsetImageName":"","Elements":null,"ImagePath":"","group_id":-1,"group_type":""},{"Index":4,"Type":"title","Text":"#  3. Behavioral Design Patterns in Java","Level":0,"Polygon":{"LeftBottom":{"X":210,"Y":649},"LeftTop":{"X":210,"Y":609},"RightBottom":{"X":788,"Y":649},"RightTop":{"X":788,"Y":609}},"InsetImageName":"","Elements":null,"ImagePath":"","group_id":-1,"group_type":""},{"Index":5,"Type":"paragraph","Text":"Behavioral design patterns are a subset of design patterns in software development that deal with the communication and interaction between objects and classes. They focus on how objects and classes collaborate and communicate to accomplish tasks and responsibilities.","Level":0,"Polygon":{"LeftBottom":{"X":202,"Y":782},"LeftTop":{"X":202,"Y":652},"RightBottom":{"X":1627,"Y":782},"RightTop":{"X":1627,"Y":652}},"InsetImageName":"","Elements":null,"ImagePath":"","group_id":-1,"group_type":""},{"Index":6,"Type":"paragraph","Text":"Types of Behavioral Design Pattern in Java:","Level":0,"Polygon":{"LeftBottom":{"X":210,"Y":868},"LeftTop":{"X":210,"Y":827},"RightBottom":{"X":797,"Y":868},"RightTop":{"X":797,"Y":827}},"InsetImageName":"","Elements":null,"ImagePath":"","group_id":-1,"group_type":""},{"Index":7,"Type":"title","Text":"##  3.1 Command Method","Level":0,"Polygon":{"LeftBottom":{"X":210,"Y":906},"LeftTop":{"X":210,"Y":872},"RightBottom":{"X":513,"Y":906},"RightTop":{"X":513,"Y":872}},"InsetImageName":"","Elements":null,"ImagePath":"","group_id":-1,"group_type":""},{"Index":8,"Type":"paragraph","Text":"Command Method is a Behavioral Design Pattern, it promotes loose coupling between the sender (client) and the receiver (the object that performs the operation) and provides a way to support undoable operations.","Level":0,"Polygon":{"LeftBottom":{"X":202,"Y":1044},"LeftTop":{"X":202,"Y":913},"RightBottom":{"X":1627,"Y":1044},"RightTop":{"X":1627,"Y":913}},"InsetImageName":"","Elements":null,"ImagePath":"","group_id":-1,"group_type":""},{"Index":9,"Type":"title","Text":"###  3.2 Iterator Method","Level":0,"Polygon":{"LeftBottom":{"X":210,"Y":1122},"LeftTop":{"X":210,"Y":1089},"RightBottom":{"X":476,"Y":1122},"RightTop":{"X":476,"Y":1089}},"InsetImageName":"","Elements":null,"ImagePath":"","group_id":-1,"group_type":""},{"Index":10,"Type":"paragraph","Text":"Iterator Method is a Behavioral Design Pattern, it provides a way to access elements of an aggregate object (a collection) sequentially without exposing the underlying representation of that collection.","Level":0,"Polygon":{"LeftBottom":{"X":202,"Y":1219},"LeftTop":{"X":202,"Y":1131},"RightBottom":{"X":1627,"Y":1219},"RightTop":{"X":1627,"Y":1131}},"InsetImageName":"","Elements":null,"ImagePath":"","group_id":-1,"group_type":""},{"Index":11,"Type":"title","Text":"####  3.3 Mediator Method","Level":0,"Polygon":{"LeftBottom":{"X":210,"Y":1300},"LeftTop":{"X":210,"Y":1265},"RightBottom":{"X":494,"Y":1300},"RightTop":{"X":494,"Y":1265}},"InsetImageName":"","Elements":null,"ImagePath":"","group_id":-1,"group_type":""},{"Index":12,"Type":"paragraph","Text":"Mediator Method is a Behavioral Design Pattern, it promotes loose coupling between objects by centralizing their communication through a mediator object. Instead of objects directly communicating with each other, they communicate through the mediator, which encapsulates the interaction and coordination logic.","Level":0,"Polygon":{"LeftBottom":{"X":202,"Y":1481},"LeftTop":{"X":202,"Y":1307},"RightBottom":{"X":1627,"Y":1481},"RightTop":{"X":1627,"Y":1307}},"InsetImageName":"","Elements":null,"ImagePath":"","group_id":-1,"group_type":""},{"Index":13,"Type":"title","Text":"#  3.4 Memento Method","Level":0,"Polygon":{"LeftBottom":{"X":210,"Y":1562},"LeftTop":{"X":210,"Y":1526},"RightBottom":{"X":502,"Y":1562},"RightTop":{"X":502,"Y":1526}},"InsetImageName":"","Elements":null,"ImagePath":"","group_id":-1,"group_type":""},{"Index":14,"Type":"paragraph","Text":"Momento Method is a Behavioral Design Pattern, it provides to save and restore the previous state of an object without revealing the details of its implementation.","Level":0,"Polygon":{"LeftBottom":{"X":202,"Y":1657},"LeftTop":{"X":202,"Y":1569},"RightBottom":{"X":1627,"Y":1657},"RightTop":{"X":1627,"Y":1569}},"InsetImageName":"","Elements":null,"ImagePath":"","group_id":-1,"group_type":""},{"Index":15,"Type":"title","Text":"##  3.5 Observer method","Level":0,"Polygon":{"LeftBottom":{"X":210,"Y":1735},"LeftTop":{"X":210,"Y":1702},"RightBottom":{"X":493,"Y":1735},"RightTop":{"X":493,"Y":1702}},"InsetImageName":"","Elements":null,"ImagePath":"","group_id":-1,"group_type":""},{"Index":16,"Type":"paragraph","Text":"Observer Method is a Behavioral Design Pattern, it defines a one-to-many dependency between objects, so that when one object (the subject) changes state, all its dependents (observers) are notified and updated automatically.","Level":0,"Polygon":{"LeftBottom":{"X":202,"Y":1873},"LeftTop":{"X":202,"Y":1742},"RightBottom":{"X":1627,"Y":1873},"RightTop":{"X":1627,"Y":1742}},"InsetImageName":"","Elements":null,"ImagePath":"","group_id":-1,"group_type":""},{"Index":17,"Type":"title","Text":"#  3.6 State Method","Level":0,"Polygon":{"LeftBottom":{"X":210,"Y":1951},"LeftTop":{"X":210,"Y":1918},"RightBottom":{"X":441,"Y":1951},"RightTop":{"X":441,"Y":1918}},"InsetImageName":"","Elements":null,"ImagePath":"","group_id":-1,"group_type":""},{"Index":18,"Type":"paragraph","Text":"State Method is a Behavioral Design Pattern, it allows an object to alter its behavior when its internal state changes.","Level":0,"Polygon":{"LeftBottom":{"X":202,"Y":2049},"LeftTop":{"X":202,"Y":1958},"RightBottom":{"X":1627,"Y":2049},"RightTop":{"X":1627,"Y":1958}},"InsetImageName":"","Elements":null,"ImagePath":"","group_id":-1,"group_type":""},{"Index":19,"Type":"title","Text":"##  3.7 Strategy Method","Level":0,"Polygon":{"LeftBottom":{"X":210,"Y":2134},"LeftTop":{"X":210,"Y":2094},"RightBottom":{"X":489,"Y":2134},"RightTop":{"X":489,"Y":2094}},"InsetImageName":"","Elements":null,"ImagePath":"","group_id":-1,"group_type":""}]}